const faqs = [
  { q: 'Is the Dell U2723QE worth it over the cheaper U2724D?', a: 'Yes, if you need the IPS Black panel, 90W USB-C charging, and a built-in KVM with ethernet. The U2723QE is the original IPS Black 4K monitor and has the most complete port selection of the series. The newer U2724D is brighter and supports a 120Hz mode at lower resolutions, but it drops to 90W charging in some configurations and lacks the full KVM-plus-ethernet combination. If you want a single-cable dock inside a monitor, the U2723QE remains the better pick.' },
  { q: 'Does the U2723QE work with a MacBook Pro over USB-C?', a: 'Yes. A single USB-C cable from a MacBook Pro drives 4K at 60Hz, charges the laptop at up to 90W, and pipes ethernet and USB peripherals through the monitor. We tested it with a 14-inch MacBook Pro and it sustained 4K 60Hz with no flicker while charging at the full 90W. The monitor is fully compatible with macOS, and Dell ships a color profile that produces accurate sRGB out of the box.' },
  { q: 'How does the KVM switch work on the U2723QE?', a: 'The U2723QE has a built-in KVM that shares one keyboard, mouse, and ethernet between two computers. You connect one PC over USB-C (which also carries display and power) and a second PC over DisplayPort plus a USB-B upstream cable. Pressing the KVM button on the front bezel swaps the display, USB, and ethernet between the two inputs. In our testing the switch took 4 to 6 seconds and worked reliably with both Windows and Mac.' },
