      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Dell U2724D</strong> is the natural alternative within Dell's own lineup. It is $100 cheaper, supports a 120Hz mode at lower resolutions, and has the same IPS Black panel. The trade-off is the loss of gigabit ethernet and a less complete port selection. If you prioritize refresh rate and do not need wired networking, the U2724D is the better buy. If you want the full dock-in-monitor package, the U2723QE is still the better pick.</p>

      <p>The <strong>ASUS ProArt PA279CV</strong> is the budget color-accurate option at $399. It has 100% sRGB coverage and 65W USB-C charging, but a standard IPS panel with half the contrast, no KVM, and no ethernet. It is a great monitor for a single Mac with no second-PC needs, but it cannot replace a dock. See our <a href="/reviews/best-usbc-dock-macbook/">USB-C dock roundup</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Apple Studio Display</strong> is the Apple-only premium alternative at $1,599. It has a beautiful glossy panel, A13-powered audio, and 12 MP webcam, but it is nearly three times the price for a standard IPS panel without KVM or ethernet. Unless you specifically want the Apple ecosystem integration, the U2723QE is a much better value.</p>

      <p>The <strong>LG 27UP650-W</strong> is the budget 4K pick at $299. It has a standard IPS panel and no USB-C charging or hub features. For a basic 4K monitor for a desktop PC, it is fine. For a single-cable laptop workstation, it does not replace a dock.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the U2723QE at full price if you want one device that combines a 4K monitor, a 90W USB-C dock, a KVM switch, and gigabit ethernet. For most hybrid workers with a USB-C laptop, this is genuinely the only peripheral on the desk — and the value of consolidating four devices into one justifies the $580 price.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. Dell runs frequent promotions on the UltraSharp line, and we have seen the U2723QE drop to $480 to $520 during Black Friday and back-to-school events. A $100 discount is meaningful and worth waiting a few weeks for if you are not in a rush.</p>

      <p>Skip the U2723QE and buy the Dell U2724D if you prioritize refresh rate, do not need wired ethernet, and want to save $100. The U2724D has the same IPS Black panel and 90W charging, with a 120Hz option and a slightly less complete port selection. It is the better pick for most users who do not need the full dock feature set.</p>

      <p>Buy the ASUS ProArt PA279CV instead if you only need a single Mac with no second-PC workflow. It is $180 cheaper, color-accurate, and has 65W USB-C charging. The trade-off is no KVM, no ethernet, and a standard IPS panel with half the contrast — but for a single-laptop setup, it is a strong value.</p>

      <p>Pair the U2723QE with a <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-light-bar/">monitor light bar</a> for late-night work without desk glare, and a <a href="/reviews/best-standing-desk-home-office/">standing desk</a> with a deep enough surface for the 24 cm stand. A <a href="/reviews/best-laptop-stand-desk/">laptop stand</a> raises your laptop screen to match the U2723QE for a cleaner dual-screen setup.</p>

